@node productinfo "The Digital Universe - product information"
 PRODUCT DESCRIPTION
 -------------------
 "The Digital Universe" is a complete astronomy program for the amateur or
professional observer.  It combines the advantages of traditional "planetarium"
programs with a  hypertext multimedia encyclopedia to create an effective
tool which assists the user in observing and learning about the heavens.

The software would not have been possible without the generous assistance
of countless individuals from the Canadian Space Agency, the National
Research Council of Canada, NASA, JPL, NORAD, the European Space Agency,
the Bureau des Longitudes, the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory, the
Russian Academy of Sciences, and several other organisations worldwide.


 PRODUCT FEATURES
 ----------------
Due to space considerations, only the major features are summarized here.

- The following databases are integrated into version 1.x of the software:
    1.  Yale Bright Star (YBS) Catalogue of 9110 stars.

    2.  Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory (SAO) Catalogue of over
        250,000 stars.
    3.  Messier's Catalogue of 110 deep sky objects (galaxies,
        nebulae, and clusters).
    4.  NGC 2000.0 Catalogue of 13,226 deep sky objects
        2007 revision
    5.  Tom Lorenzin's "1000+" database of observing comments for
        over 2000 objects.
    6.  9700 Satellites, 150,000 Asteroids and 2600 Comets. *
    * Full version only.

- The software can generate accurate stellar views of the night sky for
  any date from 100,000 BC to 100,000 AD.

- The package includes over 700 pages of hypertext, including an
  introduction to astronomy, dictionary of terms, biographies of famous
  people, celestial object descriptions, and summaries of interplanetary
  spacecraft.

- A context-sensitive help system, linked into the online encyclopedia,
  is integrated into the software. Bubble help is also available for
  many functions.

- The user can select whether or not they want to consider effects such
  as precession, proper motion, nutation, aberration, or refraction.

- "The Digital Universe" uses the latest analytic theories of motion for
  the planets (VSOP87) and their satellites, resulting in typical
  accuracies of better than 1 arcsecond (1/3600th of a degree).

- The current analytic theory of motion for the moon (ELP2000-85) has
  been extended to improve its accuracy even further for times within
  a few hundred years of the present.  The extension was done specifically
  for "The Digital Universe".

  * An even more accurate version has been developed for the forthcoming
  version 2 of The Digital Universe.

- NORAD's SGP4 model of orbital motion is used to accurately predict
  the apparent positions and movement of Earth-orbiting satellites.
  "The Digital Universe" can work with standard "2-line" orbit files.
  Hundreds of satellites are included with the software, and information
  is provided to explain how to obtain future data sets as new
  satellites are launched and older orbits decay.

- "The Digital Universe" accurately computes orbits for the moons of:

     Earth:   Our Moon
     Mars:    Phobos and Deimos
     Jupiter: Io, Europa, Ganymede, Callisto, Amalthea, and Thebe
     Saturn:  Mimas, Enceladus, Tethys, Dione, Rhea, Titan, Hyperion,
              Iapetus, Phoebe, Telesto, Calypso, and Helene
     Uranus:  Miranda, Ariel, Umbriel, Titania, and Oberon
     Neptune: Triton and Nereid
     Pluto:   Charon

- When zoomed in to most planets and satellites, the object's
  orientation and phase is determined and a latitude/longitude grid
  superimposed if the user desires.  Maps of all* the planets and
  many of their satellites are incorporated into the software
  to generate accurate renditions of the appearance of these objects.
  * Full version only.

  The ring systems of Saturn and Uranus are rendered.

- Supports the Amiga preferences printer and TurboPrint.  Plots of star
  charts, etc. are far more than a simple screen dump.  The maximum
  resolution of the printer is utilised.

  - The user can enter his or her own horizon, if desired.  Horizons for
  multiple observing sites can be configured.

- The user can select their location from a list of over 1000 cities,
  or enter their latitude, longitude, and altitude above sea level
  manually if higher accuracy is desired.

- A report generation feature lets you choose between a wide variety
  of data and customize tabular reports.  They may either be printed
  or saved to disk or copied to the Amiga's clipboard for pasting
  directly into documents.

- Provided that you have sufficient video memory, the screen upon which
  "The Digital Universe" runs can be of any size.  If the screen is
  larger that can fit on the monitor, you can scroll around simply by
  moving your mouse to the edge of the visible area.  A screenmode
  requester is provided to allow users to specify a custom screenmode.

- All development was done entirely on Amiga.  It is not a port from
  the IBM or Macintosh world.  As a result, the software closely
  adheres to the Amiga style guidelines and behaves in the manner you
  would expect from Amiga software.


 SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS
 -------------------
 The software will run on an Amiga with Workbench 4.0 or greater, and
 also need MUI v3.9 or greater (provided with Amiga OS4).

 See @{"http://www.digitaluniverse.org.uk/requirements.html"   system "c:run >nil: c:openurl http://www.digitaluniverse.org.uk/requirements.html >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"}

@endnode

@node Arexx "Digital Universe Arexx Commands"
AREXX SUPPORT


Though not fully supported until version 2.0, version 1.5 of "The Digital Universe"
does have a few very basic Arexx commands. A demonstration script Arexx is included
in this distribution.

Arexx scripts have to be run from a workbench CLI window, until version 2 there is
no way to run scripts from within "The Digital Universe".

To find out what commands "The Digital Universe" supports (in fact the same method
will output the commandset for any MUI application) type the following into a shell
window and then view the file in RAM: called arexx.txt.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill}rx "ADDRESS DUOS4; 'HELP FILE=RAM:arexx.txt'"@{bg back}@{fg text}

Note "The Digital Universe" needs to be running for the above line to work, or the
port "DUOS4" will not be found !


The current commands supported are shown below. Currently no Arexx commands support
the use of parameters and are just single keywords.

Standard-Commands:

Command      Template
-------      --------
QUIT         FORCE/S
HIDE
SHOW
INFO         ITEM/A
HELP         FILE/A


Commands for application "DigitalUniverse":

Command                         Template
-------                         --------
ZOOMIN
ZOOMOUT
UNDO
REDO
FULLVIEW
MEDIUMVIEW
CENTREMOUSE
AUTOADVANCE
MANUALADVANCE
TIMEINCREASE
TIMEDECREASE
SETCURRENTTIME
SCREENTOFRONT
SCREENTOBACK

LOOKNORTH
LOOKNORTHEAST
LOOKEAST
LOOKSOUTHEAST
LOOKSOUTH
LOOKSOUTHWEST
LOOKWEST
LOOKNORTHWEST

MOVENORTH
MOVENORTHEAST
MOVEEAST
MOVESOUTHEAST
MOVESOUTH
MOVESOUTHWEST
MOVEWEST
MOVENORTHWEST

FINDPLANET             NAME/F        Finds the named planet, if the name cannot
                                     be found or no parameter is supplied then
                                     the command will open the Find  ->  Sun,
                                     Planets, Moons window.
@endnode
